args:
Elysium urges Midgardsormr to join him in
bringing judgment to humans, but he refuses.
Alberius and Chthonius then appear, and the
hero challenges Elysium to a decisive battle
in order to save his people.
Blast it all, these fiends just keep coming!\nDon't let them break through to the city!
Dragons! Clearly the hero Alberius\nhas brought reinforcements!
The time for humans to be judged is nigh;\nyour lives have no place in a perfect world.
You will join me in this work,\nMidgardsormr.
Should you summon a stormwind into\nthis blaze, this land will be reduced to\nash and ruin in an instant.
People are weak and sinful, and think\nnot a whit for the order of the world\nif it conflicts with their own self-interest.

And thus this pruning is needed.
Dragons are the arbiters of the world,
and we must act to ensure that balance
is never threatened.
Now fulfill your duty as one of the race\ncharged with preserving the world and\nproceed with the culling.
Mighty dragons, I beg you to quell your\nfury and fight at our side! Nnngh...
In the short period I have associated with\nhumans, their foolishness has proved\nitself again and again.
They take away what others have created\nand betray trusted fellows for profit.
Worst of all, they hold dreams and\nproclaim ideals far beyond their purview.\nYes, they are well and truly fools.
And yet, for some reason I cannot discern,\nI cannot scorn him as I do other fools.
I cannot do as you bid me, Elysium.\nI cannot take human lives.
You understand this goes against the way\nof the world that I have laid out, yes?
I can scarce believe the human whelp\nlocated me so quickly.
Then you are attached to this man\njust as the Windwyrm is?

I once thought as you do, Holywyrm:
that humans are weak, possessed of
fleeting life, and are our charges
to be protected.
Then why have you done this thing?
Because I must ascertain whether or not\nhumans truly ARE weak, fleeting creatures\nin need of governing.
Perhaps it is that rule itself that is wrong.
A foolish line of thought. It is precisely\nbecause it is correct that it has continued\nto serve as rule.
Perhaps. However, I am not the only one\nto go against that way of things because\nof such thinking. Right, Midgardsormr?
A dragon once said to me that if we are\nthe way of things, then the sentiments\nwe feel are also a part of this way.
After he spoke, I wondered if the way of\nthings could change as our sentiments do.
As of yet, I still do not know\nif such a thing is possible.
Let us have hope. At the very least,\nYOU were able to change, yes?
I believe that change started from the\nmoment you met the young man here\nand were captivated by his radiance.
Evidently neither of you can behold\nthe grander scheme in play.
Rather than gazing only at the limited area\nbefore you, you ought to take a wider look\nat the world entire.
It's true that humans brought the Other\nback, and I understand why you have\nlost faith in our ability.
But I won't abandon my ideals—I will\ndefeat the Other, save the Ilian Church,\nand create a future alongside dragons.

I do this because I believe without a shred
of doubt that a broader society where
humans and dragons live together is
waiting for us just ahead.
And that's why I'm going to stop you!
The sacred sword is a portion of my power.\nI cannot be stopped with it.

Give in, and gain peace in the knowledge
that I will not lay waste to all humanity,
but merely cull those who serve as origin
of the conflict as I dispatch the Other.
You have but to remain a child of man\nand no more, Alberius.
Heh. You sound like an overprotective\nmother telling her kid to stay a kid.
But as I said before, I won't give up.
I want to help everyone—and not just\npeople, but also dragons and the very\nworld itself!
This is MY dream, and it doesn't matter\nif I borrowed some of your power,\nbecause my own heart led me here.
I don't require the sword to stop you...\nI have all the strength I need inside me!
It's fine if he is a fool, for thus does light\nshine, straight and unwavering.
I will oppose the Holywyrm alongside you,\nAlberius—and I imagine Midgardsormr\nwill do the same as well.
I will. Ah, but if we are doing so...
Yes, if we are to protect each other, I am\nmore accustomed to doing so in this way.
I'm counting on you to watch my back.
...So be it. Before I battle the Other,\nI will put all of you in your place.
Let light shine upon heaven and earth.
This world will fall to order—and the\nchildren of man will be judged!
